2. UX Analysis

2.1 Scaling & Real Estate of UI Elements
One pattern that is prevalent in the qualitative analysis is the issue regarding the
scaling of the Navigation Bar. According to respondents like Stanley, Josh, and Evie-
Mae, the Navbar takes up too much space. "In terms of UX, this means 'interface
crowding', meaning it will distract from its main task, which is choosing products."
"The nav bar was too large... make the navbar smaller and more fitted." - Stanley
Thompson-Thorn
2.2 User Interaction Patterns
The use of the Dropdown menu to order was found problematic by respondent Danil
Vassiljev. Scrolling through the menu is considered difficult and unnecessary since the
open grid would allow seeing all produce in one look.

3. Back-end & Database Integrity Analysis

3.1 Code-to-Database Mapping
The technical audience conducted a "white box" assessment of the code's back end database parts. One positive finding is Naming Convention Synchronicity. The fact that there is consistency between identifiers in the SQL schema and the file names in PHP greatly aids maintainability.

Technical Findings:
Password Hashing: Confirmed to be functional and secure (non-plaintext).
Relationships: Orders are correctly tied to 'username' fields, including appropriate
foreign key usage.
Computed Columns: Correct total calculation logic applies the delivery charge of
£2.50 in case of 'method' = 'Delivery'.

